qx||cs|6|fp|1|ht|b|at|^-{      DOUBLES (PART 1) - NEGATIVE DOUBLE
    Larry Cohen - Date of publish: 9/1/2014 - Level: Intermediate    
}^-|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BLarry Cohen: ^*N|cp||at|There are two crucial issues to discuss and two smaller ones. First the big stuff:|
PG| ***** 9 ***** |


AT|

^*B1. Through what level?^*N
^C@2Many players mark their convention card: "through 2@S" or "through 3@S." This is not a good agreement. If you are writing "through 3@S," do you mean to tell me that when the opponents overcall, say, 4@C, that you magically expect to have a trump stack and want to double 4@C for penalties? Pretty silly. I recommend Negative Double "through infinity." In fact, the higher they bid, the less likely you are ever to be dealt a penalty double. Doubles on any level should NOT show length/strength in the opponent's suit. They should all be takeout/cards.So, don't limit yourselves by marking through 2@S or 3@S.|
PG| ***** 10 ***** |


AT|

^B@22^*B. What suits does the negative double show?^*N
^C@2In general, the other major(s) is promised. If responder can't stand a suit that opener selects, he needs to have a backup plan (often tolerance for opener's first suit). If the opening is 1-of-a-major and they overcall the other major, a negative double typically shows both minors.|
PG| ***** 11 ***** |


cp|8|AT|

^B@2^*BHoward Schutzman: ^*N|cp||at|I agree with Cohen in principle. However, I am slightly more precise. I like to play negative doubles through 3@S, meaning a double of an opponent's overcall through 3@S shows support for the unbid major. Starting at the 4-level doubles are "card showing" but do not promise any particular distribution. They are neither purely penalty nor purely takeout. They mean "partner, do something intelligent". The more distributional partner is the more partner should want to bid. The flatter partner is, the more partner should want to pass.|
PG| ***** 12 ***** |


NT||
