^B@2^*BLarry Cohen: ^*N|cp||at|The "smaller" issues are the following two specific auctions, which unfortunately require memorization:|
pg| ***** 13 ***** |


ht|g|at|^B{|ia|,1c1dx|at|}|ht|g|at|^k@2In this exact auction, the double promises both majors (at least 4-4). With only one 4 card major, the responder simply bids it (promising at least 4).|
pg| ***** 14 ***** |


ht|k|at|^B{|ia|,1c1hx|at|}|ht|k|at|^k@2On this specific auction, the double promises exactly 4 spades. With 5 or more, the responder bids 1@S.|
PG| ***** 15 ***** |


ht|o|at|^B@2These 2 auctions cause confusion among inexperienced players. There is no substitute or shortcut for these 2 "special" rules. They simply need to be studied, studied again, then practiced and memorized.|
PG| ***** 16 ***** |


AT|

When playing Negative Double, what if the responder happens to have a penalty double? The way to "get them" is to pass (in tempo is a good idea) and hope the opening bidder can reopen with his own takeout double, to be converted for penalties.|
PG| ***** 17 ***** |


